==English==
{{wikipedia|Live by the sword, die by the sword}}

===Etymology===
'''1611,''' {{w|King James Version of the Bible}}, {{w|Gospel of Matthew}}, [[s:Bible (King James)/Matthew#Chapter 26|26:52]]
:* Then said Jesus unto him, "Put up again thy sword into his place: for all they that take the sword shall perish with the sword."

===Proverb===
{{head|en|proverb}}

# One who uses {{l|en|violence}} can expect a violent {{l|en|response}}; it is better to try to use {{l|en|peaceful}} means wherever possible.
# {{lb|en|figuratively}} One can expect dire outcomes from any vice; {{non-gloss definition|used to convey a sense that {{l|en|poetic justice}} is inevitable}}.
# {{lb|en|figuratively}} The means of one's {{l|en|success}} can become the means of one's {{l|en|downfall}}.
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=October 17 1997|passage=And in Dirk Diggler's most anguished scene, as he shouts at Jack Horner, "I'm ready to shoot my scene RIGHT NOW!" we learn that those who '''live by the sword''' can also '''die by it'''.|author=Roger Ebert|newspaper=Chicago Sun-Times|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/boogie-nights-1997|title=Boogie Nights (1997) review}}
#* '''2009''', Larry Downes, ''The Laws of Disruption: Harnessing the New Forces That Govern Life and Business in the Digital Age'', Basic Books {{ISBN|9780465019984}}
#*: In the “'''live by the sword, die by the sword'''” category of ironic litigation, consider the fate of struggling hardware and software maker Sun Microsystems.

